Reposting with some modified information. I don’t care if you aren’t interested. Fuck you.

Crab-eating foxes (also known as forest foxes, wood foxes, or maikongs) are a canine native to South America. They are not true foxes.

They form monogamic pairs to travel, hunt, and mate. They spend their time in their dens during the day (often stolen from a different animal, although they are capable of tunneling) and hunt during the night. They make use of several different sounds; including barking, howling, and whirring sounds. Often when a pair is separated. They are territorial, but are less so during the wet seasons where food is more abundant.

Per it’s name, it searches for crabs on floodplains during the wet season, but it’s an opportunistic omnivore, and includes a vast amount of different animals in its diet. During the dry season, the tend to eat more insects. They seem to be rather docile, but that’s based on my own time watching videos of them. Breeding pair is monogamous and reproduction is not fixed to certain times of the year. They mate for life.

There are literally no crab-eating fox waifurs both in written and visual form. Go to e6 and check yourself.

Quoted By: >>31107543
>>31107212
tropical birds have the advantage of their bright colors fitting in with tropical environments. in temperate climates, or highly seasonal climates, you tend to see the drab-female, bright-male dichotomy. the female blends in with the nest and foliage and the male will distract would be predators. bright colors are also a risky signal for fitness which helps females in mate selection.

predatory birds look the same because they are usually on top of their food chain and don't have to worry about that. Birds that travel in flocks gain an advantage from all looking the same as well.
